<h2>For Latin Catholics</h2>

<p>If you are already a Roman Catholic, you have a standing invitation. You can attend any Byzantine Catholic parish, participate fully in the Divine Liturgy, and receive the Eucharist. You do not need anyone's permission. The Byzantine Catholic churches are in full communion with Rome — what is celebrated at the altar is the same Body and Blood of Christ you receive at your Latin parish, offered in a different rite but within the same Catholic communion.</p>

<p>Many Latin Catholics discover in the Byzantine tradition something they have been missing without knowing it — a deeper sense of mystery in worship, a richer theology of the spiritual life, a tradition that has preserved elements of early Christianity that the West has attenuated. You are welcome to "bi-ritual" — attending both your Latin parish and a Byzantine parish. Some Latin Catholics eventually transfer their canonical enrollment to a Byzantine Catholic church, a process that requires the permission of both bishops but is neither unusual nor difficult.</p>

<p>You lose nothing by exploring the Eastern tradition. You gain a second lung.</p>

<h2>For Orthodox Christians</h2>

<p>This is the most delicate paragraph in this entire journey, because the relationship between Byzantine Catholics and Orthodox Christians is complex, painful, and full of history. We will not pretend otherwise.</p>

<p>Byzantine Catholics and Orthodox share virtually everything: the same Liturgy, the same theology, the same spirituality, the same Fathers, the same icons. The difference is ecclesiological — the question of communion with Rome. For some Orthodox, Byzantine Catholics represent an unacceptable compromise: an Eastern shell with a Western soul. For Byzantine Catholics, they represent the opposite: a bridge, a witness that Eastern and Western Christianity can coexist in communion.</p>

<p>If you are Orthodox and feel called toward communion with Rome — for whatever reason — the door is open, and a Byzantine Catholic parish will feel like home. The transition involves no repudiation of your Orthodox faith or practice. You will celebrate the same Liturgy, venerate the same icons, and follow the same spiritual traditions you have always known. What changes is the canonical reality: you enter into communion with the Bishop of Rome while retaining your Eastern identity in full.</p>

<p>We do not proselytize. We do not claim that our way is the only way. We simply exist — and we leave the rest to the Holy Spirit.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— Metropolitan Andrey Sheptytsky, Letter to the Faithful, 1942">
  Love your own rite, your own Church, your own tradition — but never at the expense of love for your brothers and sisters in Christ, wherever they may worship.
</Pullquote>

<h2>For Those New to Christianity</h2>

<p>Perhaps you have come to this journey with no Christian background at all. Perhaps you are exploring Christianity for the first time, and the Byzantine tradition is simply the form in which you first encountered it. If so, welcome — you are in distinguished company. Some of the greatest saints in the Eastern tradition were converts from other faiths or from no faith at all.</p>

<p>The Eastern Church does not require you to check your intellect at the door. It does not ask you to accept a set of propositions on blind faith. It asks you to enter into an experience — the experience of worship, of beauty, of prayer, of community — and to see whether, within that experience, you encounter the living God. The theology comes later, as a reflection on the encounter. The encounter comes first.</p>

<p>Talk to a priest. Attend Liturgy. Read the Gospels. Pray — even if you are not sure anyone is listening. The Eastern tradition has great patience with seekers. It took some saints decades to find their way home. There is no deadline.</p>

