<h2>Finding a Parish</h2>

<p>Byzantine Catholic parishes exist throughout North America, Europe, the Middle East, and increasingly in other parts of the world. Here are some resources for finding one near you:</p>

<p><strong>In the United States:</strong> The Byzantine Catholic Metropolitan Church of Pittsburgh maintains a parish directory. The Ruthenian, Ukrainian, Melkite, and other Eastern Catholic eparchies each have their own websites with parish locators.</p>

<p><strong>In Canada:</strong> The Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Edmonton, the Eparchy of Toronto, and the Slovak Eparchy of Saints Cyril and Methodius all maintain directories.</p>

<p><strong>Worldwide:</strong> The Catholic Near East Welfare Association (CNEWA) provides information on Eastern Catholic communities globally.</p>

<p>If there is no Byzantine Catholic parish near you, an Orthodox parish will offer a virtually identical liturgical experience — though intercommunion is not possible. And any Latin Catholic parish will, of course, welcome you into the same Catholic communion, even if the rite is different.</p>

<h2>An Invitation, Not a Conclusion</h2>

<p>This journey has covered a great deal of ground — from the <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#divine-liturgy">Divine Liturgy</a> to the icons, from the Trinity to the saints, from the Great Schism to the hope of reunion. But a website can only do so much. The real journey begins when you walk through actual doors into an actual church, where actual people are singing actual hymns to an actually present God.</p>

<p>The <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#theotokos">Theotokos</a> waits in the apse. The saints watch from the walls. The incense rises. The priest chants: <em>"Blessed is the Kingdom of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, now and ever and unto ages of ages."</em></p>

<p>And the people respond: <strong>"Amen."</strong></p>

<p>Come and see.</p>

